Greatest Common Divisor (GCD)
Find GCD of two numbers using a for loop.

Example:
Input: 12, 18 â†’ GCD = 6

ðŸ”¹ GCD (Greatest Common Divisor)

The Greatest Common Divisor (also called HCF â€“ Highest Common Factor) of two numbers is the largest number that divides both numbers exactly (without remainder).

ðŸ”¹ Example 1:

Find GCD of 12 and 18.

Divisors of 12 â†’ 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 12

Divisors of 18 â†’ 1, 2, 3, 6, 9, 18

Common divisors â†’ 1, 2, 3, 6
ðŸ‘‰ Greatest = 6
âœ”ï¸ So, GCD(12, 18) = 6

ðŸ”¹ Example 2:

Find GCD of 8 and 20.

Divisors of 8 â†’ 1, 2, 4, 8

Divisors of 20 â†’ 1, 2, 4, 5, 10, 20

Common divisors â†’ 1, 2, 4
ðŸ‘‰ Greatest = 4
âœ”ï¸ So, GCD(8, 20) = 4

ðŸ”¹ Example 3:

Find GCD of 7 and 13.

Divisors of 7 â†’ 1, 7

Divisors of 13 â†’ 1, 13

Common divisors â†’ 1
ðŸ‘‰ GCD(7, 13) = 1
(These are called co-prime numbers because their GCD is 1).

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int a, b, i, gcd = 1;

    // Input
    printf("Enter two numbers: ");
    scanf("%d %d", &a, &b);

    // Find GCD using for loop
    for (i = 1; i <= a && i <= b; i++) {
        if (a % i == 0 && b % i == 0) {
            gcd = i;
        }
    }

    // Output
    printf("GCD of %d and %d is %d\n", a, b, gcd);

    return 0;
}




